post_text:
Supportive Parents,

Lewis Cass Schools is hosting an elementary / middle robotics tournament on November 2nd. We need parents who would willingly support their little kings by volunteering some time. Before you say, I don't know anything about robotics....you truly do not need to know anything about robotics to fill the spots. You can be trained in about 5 minutes in the morning/afternoon of the event. For instance, scoring is just tapping the screen and it adds the score up for you. You will get to work with elementary students from all over the state. The tournament runs from 8 to 4, but you can do a morning or afternoon slots. If you can do an afternoon slot that would be awesome as it harder to fill those slots. You will get lunch AND be helping out your little kings here at Cass.

If you would be interested in helping, please fill out the parent volunteer form below. If you have any questions, feel free to email me. Its great to be a King!

https://forms.gle/mH3dwaePeSqSWocD8

Matthew Snoeberger
Director of Technology
Lewis Cass Schools
snoebergerm@lewiscass.net

post_text: IRON Kings returned to FRC Robotics this season finishing our first meet in the quarterfinals and semifinals in our second, missing state by five points. Robotics combines the excitement of sport with the rigors of science and technology. We call FIRST Robotics Competition the ultimate Sport for the Mind. High-school student participants call it “the hardest fun you’ll ever have.” The students have a six week build time to put together a robot which translates into four-hour practices every night and eight-hour Saturdays for the build season. I love robotics because its one of the very few sports that every team member can go pro.

post_text:
Lewis Cass High School Receives National Athletic Trainers' Association Safe Sports School Award

Walton, IN, 2019 - Lewis Cass Jr-Sr High School is the recipient of the National Athletic Trainers' Association (NATA) Safe Sports School award for its Kings Athletic Programs. The award champions safety and recognizes secondary schools that have met the recommended standards to improve safety in sports. The award reinforces the importance of providing the best level of care, injury prevention, and treatment. See full story here.

http://www.lewiscass.net/national-athletic-trainers-association-safe-sports-school-award/

post_text:
LCHS Performance Qualified High School

The Indiana Department of Education and the Office of School Accountability & Accreditation congratulates Lewis Cass high school for their 2016-17 A-F school performance! Lewis Cass high school has received the status of a Performance Qualified High School for the 2018-19 school year. The Performance Qualified High School program is in state statute.

In order to be eligible for the performance qualified program, a high school must receive an A for the previous school year. A high school remains designated as a qualified high school until it either receives a C or lower for one school year, or receives a B or lower for two consecutive school years.

Read the full article here...http://www.lewiscass.net/lchs-performance-qualified-high-school-for-the-2018-19/

post_text:
School Text Alerts - Parents
With our new call out system it now allows you as a parent to decide whether or not to receive text messages directly from your phone and also allows you to opt-in/out at anytime without having to contact the school. In order to opt-in or start receiving messages you will receive a text message on Friday, January 19th at 10:00 am from 67587. If you want to receive text messages, just reply back with a Y or Yes. You will receive a confirmation that you are registered to receive messages. If you do not want to receive text messages, just ignore the message. If for some reason you do not receive the text message after 10:00 am on Friday just follow the instructions listed here https://drive.google.com/file/d/1ZWjEV1rWvA1yMn_sAT8rOeFZnJTSDQEu/view.

You will not be able opt-in to receive messages before 10:00 am on Friday.

post_text: The Lewis Cass FFA will be having a live Worker Auction and Pork Chop Dinner on Friday, February 26, 2016. We will start serving at 4:30 pm and stop serving at 7:00 pm. The worker auction starts at 7:00 pm. If you would like to purchase tickets for the dinner please contact an FFA member at a discount of $2 less per meal. Meal tickets purchased that night will be $12 for a 2 chop meal, $10 for a single chop meal, and $7 for a hot dog meal. Carry out is available that evening.

post_text:
**IMPORTANT INFORMATION FOR PARENTS, STUDENTS, AND STAFF**

The original plan was to do an eLearning day on Friday, February 13th as a trial to see how it ran. However, since we now are experiencing our second eLearning day, we will attend school as a regular school day on Friday, February 13th. Although eLearning days are a good option to make-up days, we believe it is more important to have our students in front of us for instruction whenever we can.
text:
**IMPORTANT INFORMATION FOR PARENTS, STUDENTS, AND STAFF**

The original plan was to do an eLearning day on Friday, February 13th as a trial to see how it ran. However, since we now are experiencing our second eLearning day, we will attend school as a regular school day on Friday, February 13th. Although eLearning days are a good option to make-up days, we believe it is more important to have our students in front of us for instruction whenever we can.
